    <item>
      <title>The Meaning of Ahamkar in Bhagwat Gita</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/wiaposts/meaning-of-ahamkar-in-bhagavad-gita/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 18 Mar 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <author>hari@dasarpai.com (Dr. Hari Thapliyaal)</author>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/wiaposts/meaning-of-ahamkar-in-bhagavad-gita/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;
    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img class=&#34;my-0 rounded-md&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; src=&#34;../../assets/images/wiapost/5292-meaning-of-ahamkar-in-bhagavad-gita.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;The Meaning of Ahamkar in Bhagwat Gita&#34; /&gt;
      
    &lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;The Meaning of Ego in Bhagwat Gita 
    &lt;div id=&#34;the-meaning-of-ego-in-bhagwat-gita&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    
    &lt;span
        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100&#34;&gt;
        &lt;a class=&#34;group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700&#34;
            style=&#34;text-decoration-line: none !important;&#34; href=&#34;#the-meaning-of-ego-in-bhagwat-gita&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;        
    
&lt;/h1&gt;


&lt;h2 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Ahamkaara vs Ego 
    &lt;div id=&#34;ahamkaara-vs-ego&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    
    &lt;span
        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100&#34;&gt;
        &lt;a class=&#34;group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700&#34;
            style=&#34;text-decoration-line: none !important;&#34; href=&#34;#ahamkaara-vs-ego&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;        
    
&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In my view, the distinction between &lt;strong&gt;Ahamkaara&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;Ego&lt;/strong&gt; is subtle yet profound, especially when viewed from a philosophical and spiritual lens. Ahamkara is &lt;strong&gt;a tool that can be refined&lt;/strong&gt;, whereas ego is &lt;strong&gt;an illusion that must be dissolved&lt;/strong&gt;. If Ahamkara leads to the realization that &lt;strong&gt;all is one&lt;/strong&gt;, it becomes a stepping stone to enlightenment. But if it binds one to the material world, it becomes just another name for ego.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>How to Overcome the Ego and Find Joy in Life?</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/wiaposts/overcome-ego-and-find-joy-in-life/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 16 Mar 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <author>hari@dasarpai.com (Dr. Hari Thapliyaal)</author>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/wiaposts/overcome-ego-and-find-joy-in-life/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;
    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img class=&#34;my-0 rounded-md&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; src=&#34;../../assets/images/wiapost/5290-overcome-ego-and-find-joy-in-life.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;Ego and Joy of Life&#34; /&gt;
      
    &lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Ego and Joy of Life 
    &lt;div id=&#34;ego-and-joy-of-life&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    
    &lt;span
        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100&#34;&gt;
        &lt;a class=&#34;group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700&#34;
            style=&#34;text-decoration-line: none !important;&#34; href=&#34;#ego-and-joy-of-life&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;        
    
&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If you think, &lt;em&gt;&amp;ldquo;The ego within us &lt;br&gt;
wants to do something difficult because, &lt;br&gt;
against the difficult, one feels, &lt;br&gt;
&amp;lsquo;I am someone, doing such a difficult thing,&amp;rsquo;&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt; &lt;br&gt;
then think again.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;It is not about seeking difficulty. &lt;br&gt;
If you challenge someone by asking, &lt;br&gt;
&lt;em&gt;&amp;ldquo;Why are you doing X in the most difficult way?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt; &lt;br&gt;
they will likely respond, &lt;br&gt;
&lt;em&gt;&amp;ldquo;This is the easiest and simplest way.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Is Ego Bad?</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/wiaposts/Is-Ego-Bad/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 15 Dec 2024 08:33:00 +0530</pubDate>
      <author>hari@dasarpai.com (Dr. Hari Thapliyaal)</author>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/wiaposts/Is-Ego-Bad/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;
    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img class=&#34;my-0 rounded-md&#34; loading=&#34;lazy&#34; src=&#34;../../assets/images/wiapost/5274-Is-Ego-Bad.jpg&#34; alt=&#34;Is Ego Bad?&#34; /&gt;
      
    &lt;/figure&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;h1 class=&#34;relative group&#34;&gt;Is Ahamkar Bad? 
    &lt;div id=&#34;is-ahamkar-bad&#34; class=&#34;anchor&#34;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    
    &lt;span
        class=&#34;absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100&#34;&gt;
        &lt;a class=&#34;group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700&#34;
            style=&#34;text-decoration-line: none !important;&#34; href=&#34;#is-ahamkar-bad&#34; aria-label=&#34;Anchor&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/span&gt;        
    
&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;First, we need to understand.&lt;br&gt;
The Sanskrit word &amp;ldquo;Ahamkara&amp;rdquo;&lt;br&gt;
is not the same as &amp;ldquo;ego.&amp;rdquo;&lt;br&gt;
Similarly, the Hindi word &amp;ldquo;Ghamand&amp;rdquo;&lt;br&gt;
is not the same as &amp;ldquo;proud.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Those who know Hindi understand,&lt;br&gt;
&amp;ldquo;Ghamand&amp;rdquo; is bad, but pride is good.&lt;br&gt;
Similarly, having Ahamkara is fine.&lt;br&gt;
But having an ego is the problem.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      
    </item>
    
